          "evidence_text_excerpt": "Tax-free First Home Savings Accounts: An overview I 4\nNon-residents of Canada\nYou can only open an FHSA if you are a resident of Canada for tax purposes.\nIf you become a non-resident of Canada after you've opened an FHSA, you can keep your FHSA in place.\nYou can continue to make contributions and may claim a tax deduction in Canada. There will be no tax in\nCanada on income earned on assets within your FHSA, but be sure to investigate how the foreign country\ntaxes an FHSA.\nIf you\u2019re a non-resident, withdrawals from your FHSA will be subject to non-resident withholding tax at a 25%\nrate since you can't make a qualifying withdrawal to build or buy a qualifying home.\nInterest deductibility, collateralization, and bankruptcy\nLike RRSPs and TFSAs, interest on money borrowed to invest in an FHSA is not tax deductible and you can't\npledge FHSA assets as collateral for a loan. In addition, FHSAs",
